card all the liquid and strained the grains... Then I put grains into a glass bottle and poured the milk. But in my first attempt I committed a mistake. I put the bottle into my RICE BOX. And after 24 hours when I checked it was over fermented.. It was looking like COTTAGE CHEESE (PANEER) So ASAP I called Mr kefir and told him everything. So he suggested me to keep the bottle in a CLAY POT filled with little water.. I did the same but here is one interesting thing (MAY BE ITS BCZ OF CLIMATE I GUESS) They say it takes atleast 24 hours to get ready kefir curd but in my case its taking only 10 to 12 hours... I am using Buffalo milk of 6 to 8 fat %age. I've checked it almost 5 times by now. Every time when I put it for 24 hours it bcm more sour (which is good) and two times I found it over fermented(which is not good for grains) Regular over fermentation kills live grains.. SO now I make kefir curd twice in a day. First I put it at 8 pm with almost 500ml buffalo milk. Then in morning I strain it at 7am. Then again I make it at 7 am and strain it 8pm. (it totes depends on the temperature of ur city u r living in) Right now here in north India its almost 43° to 45 ° My curd which is almost look like THICK LASSI is doing great... Mr. Kefir is also very nice and helpful person who showed me the right way... M very health conscious guy... May be in the beginning some will think 1200 bucks are tooooo much for only a few grains (which u even can count) but believe me for a lifetime its just nothing (1200 rs) (according to me). Now my grains are healthy and within a month it grows almost two teaspoon. The pic I've shared is almost 15 days old... There are nothing like big or small grains in size only what matters is how healthy grains u have....Its up on you how to treat them..... Well guys I gave 4 star for is it easy to use or not bcz dealing with live kefir grains is very delicate job. Especially if u r a beginner (like me) it requires lots of care... So its not easy to handle it... I know guys u have done ur homework on kefir grains (how healthy they are) so M not gonna lecture on that... In the end if any of you think my review could help you leading a healthy life then please gimme a like... But if not then its okita.... Regards Amit Verma Amit Verma 5.0 out of 5 stars Both thumbs up. Reviewed in India 🇮🇳 on 13 May 2022 Well no doubt product is excellent... Before buying I was wondering that it might get damag via transportation. But I got surprised when I saw kefir grains were almost quarter teaspoon (small) with one teaspoon of milk. Well I discard all the liquid and strained the grains... Then I put grains into a glass bottle and poured the milk. But in my first attempt I committed a mistake. I put the bottle into my RICE BOX. And after 24 hours when I checked it was over fermented.. It was looking like COTTAGE CHEESE (PANEER) So ASAP I called Mr kefir and told him everything. So he suggested me to keep the bottle in a CLAY POT filled with little water.. I did the same but here is one interesting thing (MAY BE ITS BCZ OF CLIMATE I GUESS) They say it takes atleast 24 hours to get ready kefir curd but in my case its taking only 10 to 12 hours... I am using Buffalo milk of 6 to 8 fat %age. I've checked it almost 5 times by now. Every time when I put it for 24 hours it bcm more sour (which is good) and two times I found it over fermented(which is not good for grains) Regular over fermentation kills live grains.. SO now I make kefir curd twice in a day. First I put it at 8 pm with almost 500ml buffalo milk. Then in morning I strain it at 7am. Then again I make it at 7 am and strain it 8pm. (it totes depends on the temperature of ur city u r living in) Right now here in north India its almost 43° to 45 ° My curd which is almost look like THICK LASSI is doing great... Mr. Kefir is also very nice and helpful person who showed me the right way... M very health conscious guy... May be in the beginning some will think 1200 bucks are tooooo 